<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06007031 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06007031 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  UNION-CITY; SMOKING; SALE; EQUIPMENT; BAN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In an effort to keep minors from lighting up, cigarette vending machines maysoon become a thing of the past in Union City.;    The city council tonight isscheduled to discuss whether to restrict the machines to bars and otherlocations that turn away minors, or to ban them all together.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  UNION CITY WEIGHS BAN ON CIGARETTE MACHINES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;Everyone knows the cigarette industry is losing customers by the thousandsevery day, and that they target young people to get them hooked,&quot; saidCouncilman Robert Garfinkle, who brought the idea up before the council lastmonth after reading an article on another California city that was consideringa ban on the machines.;    This month, Rancho Mirage, a desert community eastof Los Angeles, became the first city in the state to prohibit the vendingmachines.;    The California cities of Duarte, Manteca and San Marcos limitcigarette vending machines to bars.;    Across the country, New York City hasbanned the sale of cigarette vending machines in most public places. Salt LakeCity and Minneapolis have enacted similar bans.;    Most states, includingCalifornia, ban the sale of cigarettes to minors. However, Garfinkle saidvending machines are rarely supervised, which allows minors free access tothem.;    &quot;A vending machine doesn't know the difference between a kid and anadult,&quot; he said. &quot;I think we should just ban them altogether.&quot;;    A millionteen-agers start smoking every year, according to government estimates, and 90percent of the nation's 50 million smokers started as teen-agers. Answeringcriticism that it profits from teen-age smoking, the tobacco industry lastmonth announced it would begin a campaign to discourage smoking by youthsunder 18.;    The Tobacco Institute, the trade group for the nation'scigarette companies, said one focus of its campaign would be to support anational legal smoking age of at least 18.;    The institute will also urgerestricting minors' access to cigarette vending machines, banning or limitingmarketing practices like billboard advertisements near schools, and providingsupport materials to parents and stores that sell tobacco products.; IF YOU'REINTERESTEDThe Union City Council will meet on the issue tonight at 8 in thecouncil chambers, 34009 Alvarado-Niles Road.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  FERNANDO QUINTERO, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910107  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  356  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday January 7, 199100007031,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>